Dr. Ray Peat mentioned the biggest animals of an ecosystem are the most important and what "pulls" it forward. E.g. seemingly destructive behavior like bears tearing up through the woods improves the overall system fertility and is far more "rational" than it seems superficially.

Allan Savory the Rhodesian farmer apparently talks about this. But basically just having those big animals living in a nearby forest might change life and even society proper in ways that are impossible to trace down directly, but still very much real.

There are examples like wolves being present in an area decreasing Lyme disease rates or making the deer healthier and more intelligent and even making people living nearby more likely to vote for far-right political parties. So bears, bisons, and wolves do more than they let on.
